[965|31950] 18:56:56.914 I/NARR-STATE: narrationState → Speaking(segment=NarrationSegment(id=newspaper_1692_1530048785936580, text=Salem, November 22, 1691. PARRIS PREACHES OF VILLAGE CURSE! Today in Salem Village, Reverend Samuel Parris delivered a powerful sermon, “The Enemies of the Covenant,” directly linking a recent dispute over his salary to a broader spiritual crisis. He warned of a gathering curse upon the village, setting a stage that will tragically resonate in the months to come. This sermon established a framework of internal enemies and divine retribution.

Today, Reverend Samuel Parris preached a sermon that, while rooted in a local dispute, took on a decidedly ominous tone. The minister, facing opposition from a growing faction within Salem Village who have challenged his salary, framed the disagreement as a spiritual battle. Parris argued that those who withheld support from the ministry were not simply political opponents, but “enemies of the covenant” actively inviting God’s wrath upon the community. He drew upon the words of the Psalmist, declaring that God will ultimately vindicate His servant, but warned that judgment would fall upon those who stood against him. As the magistrate’s record of the sermon reveals, Parris passionately asserted, “I feel it in the air. I smell it on the wind. There is something dark gathering at the edges of this village." Thomas Putnam Jr. sat in the front row, visibly nodding in agreement, while Joseph Porter remained stoic, a clear sign of the deepening divisions within the village. This sermon, delivered two months before the first accusations of witchcraft, laid the groundwork for a climate of fear and suspicion that would soon engulf Salem Village.

Reverend Samuel Parris delivered his sermon, “The Enemies of the Covenant,” today, explicitly connecting the recent dispute over his salary to a larger spiritual threat. He characterized those who opposed his financial support as “enemies of the covenant” and warned of divine retribution.

Parris drew heavily on scripture, specifically Psalm 110:1, to justify his position, stating, “The LORD said unto my Lord, Sit thou at my right hand, until I make thine enemies thy footstool.” He applied this passage to his own situation, suggesting God would ultimately vindicate his ministry.

The sermon created a palpable tension within the meetinghouse, visibly affecting members of both factions. Thomas Putnam Jr. actively signaled his support, while Joseph Porter remained detached and unyielding.

Ann Putnam Sr. appeared deeply disturbed by Parris’s warnings about a gathering curse, her anxieties amplified by personal tragedies and the uncertain times.

Mercy Lewis, a young woman who experienced trauma from a frontier raid, seems to have connected Parris’s talk of “enemies” to the dangers she knew from the wilderness, internalizing a sense of fear.

Abigail Williams, Parris’s niece, observed the sermon with intense focus, absorbing the atmosphere of anger and perceived threat within the parsonage.

Francis Nurse, while concerned for the well-being of the community, appeared wary of Parris’s escalating rhetoric and the potential for division.

The sermon significantly polarized the village, strengthening the resolve of Parris’s supporters while further entrenching his opponents and solidifying the lines of conflict., type=LONG_NARRATION, poiName=Salem 1692 — 1691-11-22, voiceId=en-au-x-auc-local, kind=ORACLE, category=null, refId=newspaper_1692, isReplay=false)) (autoPlay=true, queueSize=0)
