[312|7428] 19:00:08.209 I/NARR-STATE: narrationState → Speaking(segment=NarrationSegment(id=poi_narration_1530237566135284, text=This was the home of Nathaniel Bowditch, whose 1802 book The New American Practical Navigator revolutionized sailing. Bowditch — a self-taught Salem native who left school at ten and apprenticed in a ship chandler's shop — taught himself calculus, Latin, and astronomy by lamplight. He went on to compute tables that let an ordinary sailor calculate longitude at sea accurately. His book is still issued by the U.S. Navy today, more than two centuries later. Every chart, every navigation table Americans use, traces back to a self-taught boy who read math books by candle in a small Salem bedroom., type=LONG_NARRATION, poiName=Nathaniel Bowditch House, voiceId=en-us-x-tpd-local, kind=POI, category=null, refId=poi_narration, isReplay=false)) (autoPlay=true, queueSize=0)
